description:
A spectacular limestone canyon in a beautiful highland area. This canyon is deep, often dark, with long sculpted travertine passages filled with emerald to aquamarine water and lots of swimming. You will rappel down steep conic travertine accretions covered with moss into grand cathedral-like grottos. Slides that shoot you out into open space 12 feet above the water. You'll want to do this canyon more than once.

This is a popular a canyon with local canyoneers. On a weekend in Feb 2022, we encountered 3 other Mexican groups going down the canyon with us.

Be sure to read the Queretaro region notes for more information on the area.

Approach

To do the shuttle, it is best to drive along the indicated path on the .kml file. If you follow Google Maps, it can route you on some shortcuts that turn into dead ends and you'll have to turn around. We found that parking just past the bridge has the most space along the side of the road. The current .kml shows the end of the route being below a switchback in the road a little before the bridge, but there isn't much space to park here. The road is heavily travelled with local vehicles.

To do the full route, follow the access trail indicated on the kml map down to the riverbed. The first half-mile or so of going down the riverbed is dry for much of the year. There is a huge dry cascade you'll need to climb down. Then you'll reach a point where a flowing side stream comes in from RDC, and immediately afterward is the first drop.

Alternatively, the lower part of this canyon is commercially guided. The main entrance point for commercial routes is shown on Google Maps as "Cañon EL INFIERNILLO". They charge the entrance fee here and you can pay for a shuttle here (price depends on where you need a ride to/from). However, the best way to do this canyon is to do both the upper and lower parts to make it worth it.

If you don't have two cars, shuttles can be difficult for this canyon. It is easiest to either drive straight to the commercial start and try to get them to drop you off at top (for the full route) and pick you up at the bottom, or find a taxi that will follow you down to the bridge to drop off your exit vehicle and then drive you up to the top.

Descent

The upper part of the full route is beautiful, with many jumps and swims, and several rappels.

Once you reach the commercial route (there is a very obvious trail coming down RDC), the first rappel can be jumped but is shallow and somewhat technical. The second is difficult to get up to the anchors and is on a thin ridge. you can jump this, it's plenty deep. the third rap is mandatory (though you could get off partway and slide/jump) and drops you into a spectacular cathedral-like grotto.

Exit

If you need a place to stay, we found the cheapest place to stay in the area was very close to the end of Infernillo. there are a few rooms below one of the roadside shops. You can contact Ruben Espinoza Olvera on the following: Cel: 4411051540
